{{Current related|date=December 2012}}
{{Violence against women}}
On the night of 16 December 2012, a [[paramedic |paramedical]] student was [[Gangrape#Gang_rape|gang rape]]d in [[Delhi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Victim-critical-three-confess-to-crime-one-more-detained/Article1-974790.aspx|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi bus gang rape: 'What is going wrong with our society?'|publisher=The Hindustan Times}}</ref> The victim and her friend boarded a bus in [[South Delhi]] after watching a movie{{efn|"A clarification: The identity of the victims has not been disclosed yet"}}, when they were beaten by a group of six males, after which the female victim was raped.<ref name="NDTV1">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/delhi-gang-rape-victim-s-friend-also-on-bus-gives-statement-in-court-307391|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape: victim's friend, also on bus, gives statement in court|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> The victim is being treated at [[Safdarjang Hospital]] where she was on [[Mechanical ventilation|ventilatory support]] for five days.<ref name="TOI3">{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Delhi-gang-rape-victim-battles-on-undergoes-fifth-surgery/articleshow/17680621.cms|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gang rape victim battles on, undergoes fifth surgery|publisher=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name="HT!">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Delhi-gangrape-doctors-say-victim-is-off-the-ventilator-has-immense-fighting-spirit/Article1-978992.aspx|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012|title=elhi gangrape: doctors say victim is off the ventilator, has 'immense fighting spirit'|publisher=The Hindustan Times}}</ref> The incident has generated widespread public anger and protests on Indian streets and international coverage.<ref name="NDTV7">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/indians-outraged-by-rape-on-moving-bus-in-capital-307365?pfrom=home-otherstories|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Indians outraged by rape on moving bus in capital|publisher=NDTV}}</ref><ref name="NDTV5">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cities/profound-anger-grief-in-india-s-streets-over-delhi-gang-rape-307455?pfrom=home-otherstories|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Profound anger, grief in India's streets over Delhi gang-rape|publisher=NDTV}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/12/19/outrage-in-india-against-gang-rape-on-bus-angry-protests-break-out-in-new-delhi/|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Gang rape on bus triggers outrage, protests across India|publisher=Fox News}}</ref> The incident was condemned by [[UN Women]], who called on the [[Government of India]] and the [[Government of Delhi]] "to do everything in their power to take up radical reforms, ensure justice and reach out with robust public services to make women<U+2019>s lives more safe and secure".<ref name="UN">{{cite web|url=http://www.unwomen.org/2012/12/un-women-condemns-gang-rape-of-delhi-student/|date=20 December 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012|title=UN Women condemns gang rape of Delhi student|publisher=UN Women}}</ref>

On Delhi Chief Minister [[Sheila Dixit]]'s suggestion, five fast track courts were approved to try the rape cases.<ref name="fasttrack">{{cite news|title=Five fast track courts approved for Delhi rape cases|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/299600/five-fast-track-courts-approved.html |date=December 19, 2012|agency=[[Deccan Herald]]|location=New Delhi|accessdate=2012-12-20}}</ref> In an interview she also said that she "hates Delhi being called 'rape capital' but it has indeed become one".<ref name="NDTVInterview">{{cite news|title=Full transcript: Hate Delhi being called 'Rape Capital', but it's become one, Chief Minister Sheila Dikshit tells NDTV|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/full-transcript-hate-delhi-being-called-rape-capital-but-it-s-become-one-chief-minister-sheila-diksh-308529 |date=December 21, 2012|agency=[[NDTV]]|location=New Delhi|accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref> The Parliament's Standing Committee on Home Affairs would meet on 27 December 2012 to discuss the issue with summons being issued to Union Home Secretary R. K. Singh and [[Delhi Police]] Commissioner Neeraj Kumar.<ref name="NDTVInterview"/> On 21 December 2012, the government promised to file the charge sheet in the case <U+201C>quickly<U+201D> and seek maximum punishment of life imprisonment for the accused.<ref name="Hindu1">{{cite news|title=Police to seek life imprisonment for rape accused|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/police-to-seek-life-imprisonment-for-rape-accused/article4226285.ece|date=December 21, 2012|agency=The Hindu|location=New Delhi|accessdate=2012-12-22}}</ref>

==Incident==
The couple was on their way home after watching ''[[Life of Pi (film)|Life of Pi]]'' at a South Delhi multiplex. The couple boarded a bus at about 9 pm when a group of men, who were on the bus, began harassing her. When her friend tried to intervene, he was gagged and then hit mercilessly with an iron rod. Five men then hit the woman with the same rod and gang-raped her while the driver kept the bus moving. At about 11 pm, the couple was thrown semi-naked onto the road. A passerby phoned the [[Delhi Police|police]], who then collected the couple and moved the pair to a hospital. The girl had been hit with the iron rod for nearly forty-five minutes.<ref name="NDTV9">{{cite web|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-gang-rape-parliamentary-standing-panel-to-meet-on-december-27/articleshow/17705878.cms|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape: Victim is fighting for life, on ventilator, say doctors|publisher=NDTV}}</ref>

On 21 December 2012, a committee of doctors was constituted by the government of Delhi to monitor the treatment of the victim and to ensure that she receives the best possible medical attention.<ref>{{cite web|title=Delhi gangrape: Committee formed to monitor girl's treatment|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Delhi-gangrape-Committee-formed-to-monitor-girl-s-treatment/Article1-977263.aspx|work=Delhi gangrape: Committee formed to monitor girl's treatment|publisher=The Hindustan Times|accessdate=21 December 2012}}</ref>

== Victims ==
The student is from [[Ballia]] district in [[Uttar Pradesh]]. The victim's male friend, aged 28, is from [[Gorakhpur]] in Uttar Pradesh and lives in [[Ber Sarai]] in Delhi.<ref>http://www.deccanherald.com/content/299074/delhi-gang-rape-victim-battles.html</ref>

== Alleged perpetrators ==
Six men have been arrested in connection with the incident.<ref name="NDTV11">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cheat-sheet/delhi-gang-rape-case-missing-sixth-attacker-arrested-from-village-in-bihar-308398|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=21 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape case: missing sixth attacker arrested from village in Bihar}}</ref>

==== Ram Singh ====
Ram Singh was the driver of the bus. He had taken the bus out for a joy ride on Sunday evening.<ref name="NDTV12">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cities/delhi-gang-rape-rapists-wanted-to-teach-girl-a-lesson-say-police-sources-306918?ndtv_rhs|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Almost all of Delhi rape victim's intestines removed|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> He was the first accused to be arrested and was produced before the Metropolitan Magistrate on 18 December 2012. He had cleaned the bus which was later impounded by the police from Sector 3 of R K Puram on 18 December 2012.<ref name="HT1">{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/India-news/NewDelhi/Delhi-gangrape-main-accused-sent-to-5-day-police-custody-refuses-identification-parade/Article1-974332.aspx|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gangrape: main accused sent to 5-day police custody, refuses identification parade|publisher=The Hindustan Times}}</ref>

==== Mukesh Singh ====
Mukesh Singh is the brother of the main accused Ram Singh.<ref name="Outlook">{{cite web|url=http://news.outlookindia.com/items.aspx?artid=784100|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Hang Me, I've Done Heinous Act: Delhi Rape Accused|publisher=Outlook India}}</ref> He was arrested by the Delhi police in [[Rajasthan]].<ref name="HT1"/>

When in the Tihar Jail, he was also assaulted by other inmates which prompted the jail officials to separate him from the rest of the inmates to protect him from further harassment. <ref name="Assault"> [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/tihar-inmates-assault-chartered-bus-driver/1048307/ Mukesh was assaulted by Tihar Jail inmates] </ref> <ref> [http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/tihar-inmates-thrash-delhi-gangrape-accused/1/238702.html India Today article on mukesh being thrashed] </ref>

==== Vinay Sharma ====
Vinay Sharma is an assistant gym instructor in Delhi<ref name="Outlook"/> and was arrested in Delhi.<ref name="HT1"/>

==== Pawan Gupta ====
Pawan Gupta is a fruit seller by profession.<ref name="Outlook"/> He was arrested in Delhi.<ref name="HT1"/>

==== Raju ====
Raju was detained by the police in Badaun, Uttar Pradesh.<ref>http://www.ibtimes.com/delhi-gang-rape-fifth-man-arrested-police-seek-life-imprisonment-958908</ref>

==== Akshay Thakur ====

Akshay Thakur studied at the Tandwa school in [[Jharkhand]]. The accused had gone to Delhi to look for a job. <ref name="Zee1">{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/bihar/police-team-questions-delhi-rape-accused-s-father-brother_817761.html|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Police team questions Delhi rape accused's father, brother|publisher=Zee News India}}</ref> He was arrested from Aurangabad in Bihar.<ref name="NDTV11"/>

== Prosecution ==

Three of the four accused <U+2014> Mukesh, Pawan and Vinay <U+2014> were produced in the Saket court on 19 December 2012, where they confessed to the crime. The court has remanded Pawan and Vinay to four-day police custody, while Mukesh was sent to judicial custody for fourteen days. Vinay Sharma confessed to beating up the victim's male friend and demanded that he himself be hanged. The third accused, Mukesh, brother of main accused Ram Singh, did not confess to the crime but agreed to undergo identification test by the victim's male friend. All the accused are facing charges under sections 365 (kidnapping or abducting), 376 (2)(g) (gang rape), 377 (unnatural offences), 394 (hurting in committing robbery) and 34 (common intention) of the Indian Penal Code. The victim's male friend testified in the court on the same day.<ref name="NDTV1"/>

On 21 December 2012, the [[Delhi High Court]] rapped the Delhi police for being "evasive" in its probe status report in providing details of its officers on patrol duty in the area covered by the bus,<ref name="MoneyLife">{{cite web|url=http://www.moneylife.in/article/high-court-slams-delhi-police-for-its-report-on-gang-rape-case/30340.html|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012|title=High Court slams Delhi Police for its report on gang rape case}}</ref> with further hearing on the matter to be taken by the court on 9 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_inept-delhi-cops-get-hc-rap_1780383|date=21 December 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012|title=Inept Delhi cops get HC rap}}</ref>

== Reactions ==

The incident has generated public anger with widespread protest organised throughout the country.<ref name="Sky News1">{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1027511/delhi-bus-gang-rape-sparks-angry-protests|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi Bus Gang Rape Sparks Angry Protests|publisher=Sky News}}</ref> Many protestors have also been demanding death penalty for the accused, which, however, is not currently permitted by the Indian constitution. Indian [[Prime Minister of India|prime minister]] [[Manmohan Singh]] defined the incident as "very upsetting" and a "heinous crime".<ref name="IE2">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/delhi-gangrape-very-upsetting-incident-pm/1047615/|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gangrape very upsetting incident: PM|publisher=The Indian Express}}</ref>

The following day, there was an uproar in the [[Indian parliament]] over the incident. MPs in both houses had set aside their regular business to discuss the gruesome rape case and demanded strict punishment for those who carried out the attack. [[Leader of the Opposition|Leader of the opposition]] in the [[Lok Sabha]], [[Sushma Swaraj]], demanded that "the rapists should be hanged".<ref name="BBC1">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-20765869|date=18 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi bus gang rape: Uproar in Indian parliament|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Congress president [[Sonia Gandhi]] had visited the [[Safdarjang Hospital]] and met doctors on duty in the anaesthesia and surgery departments to get an update on the victim<U+2019>s condition.<ref name="IE1">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/delhi-gangrape-shakes-parliament--sushma-swaraj-others-seek-death-penalty/1047359/|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gangrape shakes Parliament; Jaya Bachchan breaks down, Sushma Swaraj, others seek death penalty|publisher=The Indian Express}}</ref> [[Bahujan Samaj Party]] chief, [[Mayawati]], said that proper investigation and strict punishment should be ensured and that the "action should be so strict that no one should dare to act in such a manner again".<ref name="BBC1"/> [[Jaya Bachchan]] said that she was <U+201C>terribly disturbed<U+201D> over the incident, and felt <U+201C>ashamed<U+201D> sitting in the House as she was <U+201C>helpless<U+201D> for <U+201C>not being able to do anything<U+201D>.<ref name="IE1"/> [[Meira Kumar]], speaker of the Lok Sabha, told reporters outside the parliament that a "new law should be brought in and must get passed to ensure the safety of women. The laws at present are not enough, we need stricter laws."<ref name="DNA1">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_delhi-gang-rape-need-stronger-laws-says-meira-kumar_1779260|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape: Need stronger laws, says Meira Kumar|publisher=The DNA}}</ref>

[[Bollywood]] actors [[Shahrukh Khan]], [[Amitabh Bachchan]], [[Salman Khan]], [[Kareena Kapoor]], [[Juhi Chawla]] and [[Gul Panag]] came out in support of the victims. <ref name="Zee2">{{cite web|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/and-more/delhi-gang-rape-shah-rukh-khan-big-b-voice-their-ire_124723.htm|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape: Shah Rukh Khan, Big B voice their ire  |publisher=Zee News}}</ref><ref name="Reuter1">{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2012/12/19/delhi-gang-rape-twitter-reactions-idINDEE8BI07N20121219|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Reactions on Twitter to the Delhi gang rape|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> Filmmaker [[Karan Johar]] tweeted, "Disgusted and apalled at the tragic rape incident in Delhi...severe and immediate punishment has to be served!!! Its{{sic}} shameful....".<ref name="Reuter1"/>

Indian cricketers [[Pragyan Ojha]], [[Harbhajan Singh]], [[Aakash Chopra]], [[Manoj Tiwary]] and [[Sanjay Manjrekar]] expressed disappointment over the incident. [[Yuvraj Singh]] wrote "shocked with the delhi rape incident. Something is terribly wrong somewhere. If this is the way women are treated God saves{{sic}} our society" on his [[twitter]] account.<ref>http://www.cricketcountry.com/cricket-articles/Delhi-gang-rape-Indian-cricketers-express-disappointment/21107</ref> Later he dedicated his Man-of-the-Match award against England to the rape victim.<ref name="Yuvraj_S">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/yuvraj-singh-dedicates-manofthematch-award-to-delhi-gangrape-victim/1048486/|accessdate=22 December 2012|title=Yuvraj Singh dedicates man-of-the-match award to Delhi gangrape victim}}</ref> Businessman [[Anand Mahindra]] asked for the social media "to sustain relentless pressure for action".<ref name="Reuter1"/>

Sitting [[Supreme Court of India|Supreme Court]] judge, Justice [[Gyan Sudha Misra]], labelled the culprits as "cobras and beasts" and that the "trial in cases relating to crimes against women needs lot of reforms".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cities/delhi-gang-rape-not-just-vips-other-people-need-security-too-says-supreme-court-judge-and-mother-of--307435|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=19 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape: Not just VIPs, other people need security too, says Supreme Court judge and mother of three|publisher=NDTV}}</ref> Author [[Chetan Bhagat]] and [[civil society]] activists [[Arvind Kejriwal]] and [[Kiran Bedi]] also voiced their anger.<ref name="Reuter1"/>

[[Sheila Dikshit]] Chief Minister of Delhi admitted that she did not have courage to meet the victim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/did-not-have-courage-to-meet-gangrape-victim-sheila-dikshit/311747-3-244.html|date=22 December 2012|accessdate=22 December 2012|title=Delhi gang-rape}}</ref>

==Protests==
Public protests took place in New Delhi on 22 December 2012 at the [[India Gate]] and [[Raisina Hill]], the later being a high-profile political area. The protesters at Raisina Hill were targeted with baton charge, [[water cannon]]s and [[tear gas]] shells by New Delhi police, in an attempt to disperse the protest. These protesters were boys and girls from different parts of Delhi with the common intention of demanding justice for the victim. The protesters from JNU, Jamia, DU and other institutes also voiced their demand for giving justice in the case of [[Soni Sori]].{aisa pamphlet from JNU on 22/12/12}. Thirteen protesters were injured in the police action.<ref>[http://zeenews.india.com/news/delhi/delhi-gang-rape-protests-live-after-lathi-charging-police-urge-protesters-to-stay-calm_818226.html "Delhi gang-rape protests".] Zeenews. 22 December 2012. Retrieved 22 December 2012.</ref>

In Kolkata, a mass rally was organised on the same day, and thousands of participants also lit candles to show their solidarity with the victim.{{cn|date=December 2012}}

